docs.abstract: France’s president is trying to tap into the country’s large pool of left-wing voters, but many are hesitant to back him.
docs.snippet: France’s president is trying to tap into the country’s large pool of left-wing voters, but many are hesitant to back him.
docs.lead_paragraph: MARSEILLE, France — On a stage erected on lush green lawns overlooking the sun-soaked Mediterranean port of Marseille, President Emmanuel Macron declared on Saturday to a crowd of supporters, “The politics that I will carry out in the next five years will be environmental, or will not be!”

headline.main: Macron Vows Ambitious Green Policies, Wooing the Left in Runoff
headline.print_headline: In Bid to Rally the Left in His Runoff With Le Pen, Macron Pledges Climate Action

docs.abstract: In several states, Republican candidates are contending with allegations of domestic violence and sexual assault. Few of their primary rivals want to talk about it.
docs.snippet: In several states, Republican candidates are contending with allegations of domestic violence and sexual assault. Few of their primary rivals want to talk about it.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When fresh allegations of domestic violence were lodged against former Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens last month, one of his Republican rivals for the state’s open Senate seat, Representative Vicky Hartzler, stepped up and called for him to end his campaign.

headline.main: As G.O.P. Candidates Face Accusations, Rivals Tread Carefully
headline.print_headline: As Republican Candidates Face Accusations, Rivals Tread Carefully

docs.abstract: After Sunday’s vote, when nearly a third of ballots went to the extreme right, a united front of mainstream voters looked more precarious than ever.
docs.snippet: After Sunday’s vote, when nearly a third of ballots went to the extreme right, a united front of mainstream voters looked more precarious than ever.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — A day after Marine Le Pen, the far-right leader, emerged as his challenger for the final round of France’s presidential election in less than two weeks, President Emmanuel Macron immediately set about on Monday to build the “dam.”

headline.main: Macron Sets Out to Build a ‘Dam’ Against Le Pen. Can It Hold?
headline.print_headline: Macron Sets Out to Build a ‘Dam’ Against Le Pen. Can It Hold Up?

byline.original: By Norimitsu Onishi and Constant Méheut

docs.abstract: New lawsuits target Representatives Paul Gosar and Andy Biggs, as well as Mark Finchem, a candidate for Arizona secretary of state, claiming they are barred from office under the 14th Amendment.
docs.snippet: New lawsuits target Representatives Paul Gosar and Andy Biggs, as well as Mark Finchem, a candidate for Arizona secretary of state, claiming they are barred from office under the 14th Amendment.
docs.lead_paragraph: A legal effort to disqualify from re-election lawmakers who participated in events surrounding the Jan. 6, 2021, attack on the Capitol expanded on Thursday, when a cluster of voters and a progressive group filed suit against three elected officials in Arizona to bar them under the 14th Amendment from running again.

headline.main: Legal Effort Expands to Disqualify Republicans as ‘Insurrectionists’
headline.print_headline: Effort Grows to Disqualify Republicans Over Jan. 6

docs.abstract: The “Plan to Rescue America” is dividing the party and cheering Democrats, and its author, Senate Republicans’ top campaign official, won’t stop talking about it.
docs.snippet: The “Plan to Rescue America” is dividing the party and cheering Democrats, and its author, Senate Republicans’ top campaign official, won’t stop talking about it.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Rick Scott of Florida, the somewhat embattled head of the Senate Republicans’ campaign arm, said one utterly indisputable thing on Thursday when he stood before a packed auditorium of supporters at the conservative Heritage Foundation: His plan for a G.O.P. majority would make everyone angry at him, Republicans included.

headline.main: Income Taxes for All? Rick Scott Has a Plan, and That’s a Problem.
headline.print_headline: A Florida Senator Is Proposing Income Taxes for All, and That’s a Problem

docs.abstract: The Democrats’ House Majority PAC is spending nearly $102 million to reserve advertising time in 51 media markets, staking out a broad battlefield for the coming midterm elections.
docs.snippet: The Democrats’ House Majority PAC is spending nearly $102 million to reserve advertising time in 51 media markets, staking out a broad battlefield for the coming midterm elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House Democrats’ main political action committee is spending nearly $102 million to reserve advertising spots in 50 media markets, from Bangor, Maine, to San Diego, Calif., a battlefield that is considerably larger and more expensive than it was in the past two congressional elections.

headline.main: A Democratic Super PAC’s Ad Buy Shows a Widening Battle for House Control
headline.print_headline: Democrats’ PAC Books Ads Across Map for Midterms

docs.abstract: Nikki Haley, the former United Nations ambassador, used a well-timed endorsement of Representative Nancy Mace to get on the opposite side of the former president.
docs.snippet: Nikki Haley, the former United Nations ambassador, used a well-timed endorsement of Representative Nancy Mace to get on the opposite side of the former president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Rumors were swirling in South Carolina early this February that Donald J. Trump would try to tear down a Republican congresswoman who had incurred his wrath.

headline.main: With Trump in Her State, Haley Finds Some Political Distance (Gently)
headline.print_headline: Haley Threads a Needle Between Trump’s Coattails and His Wrath

docs.abstract: His challenge is to promise continuity with the ruling party’s policies, yet distinguish himself from the current president.
docs.snippet: His challenge is to promise continuity with the ruling party’s policies, yet distinguish himself from the current president.
docs.lead_paragraph: South Korea’s leading liberal candidate, Lee Jae-myung, started his presidential bid with a speech that spoke squarely to the country’s simmering angst and its struggling middle class.

headline.main: Lee Jae-myung is a technocrat with hardscrabble origins.

docs.abstract: Mr. Yoon, the leading conservative candidate, hopes to win the election by appealing to South Koreans who are deeply dissatisfied with the outgoing administration.
docs.snippet: Mr. Yoon, the leading conservative candidate, hopes to win the election by appealing to South Koreans who are deeply dissatisfied with the outgoing administration.
docs.lead_paragraph: As a star prosecutor, Yoon Suk-yeol, the leading conservative candidate, helped imprison two former presidents as well as the head of Samsung and a former chief justice of the country’s Supreme Court on charges of corruption.

headline.main: Yoon Suk-yeol helped prosecute presidents. Now he wants to be one.
